### estimateBitMaskedAndLowerBound() {#a437967d8acddbcdb8cb345412f22f9dd}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>static APInt estimateBitMaskedAndLowerBound (<a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/target/lib/target/aarch64/aarch64promoteconstant-cpp/#a90f8350fecae261c25be85d38b451bff">const</a> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/constantrange">ConstantRange</a> &amp; LHS, <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/target/lib/target/aarch64/aarch64promoteconstant-cpp/#a90f8350fecae261c25be85d38b451bff">const</a> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/constantrange">ConstantRange</a> &amp; RHS)</>}
  labels = {["static"]}>
Estimate the &#39;bit-masked AND&#39; operation&#39;s lower bound.

E.g., given two ranges as follows (single quotes are separators and have no meaning here),

LHS = &#91;10&#39;00101&#39;1, ; LLo 10&#39;10000&#39;0&#93; ; LHi RHS = &#91;10&#39;11111&#39;0, ; RLo 10&#39;11111&#39;1&#93; ; RHi

we know that the higher 2 bits of the result is always 10; and we also notice that RHS&#91;1:6&#93; are always 1, so the result&#91;1:6&#93; cannot be less than LHS&#91;1:6&#93; (i.e., 00101). Thus, the lower bound is 10&#39;00101&#39;0.

The algorithm is as follows,
<ul>
<li>we first calculate a mask to find the higher common bits by Mask = ~((LLo ^ LHi) | (RLo ^ RHi) | (LLo ^ RLo)); Mask = clear all non-leading-ones bits in Mask; in the example, the Mask is set to 11&#39;00000&#39;0;</li>
<li>calculate a new mask by setting all common leading bits to 1 in RHS, and keeping the longest leading ones (i.e., 11&#39;11111&#39;0 in the example);</li>
<li>return (LLo &amp; new mask) as the lower bound;</li>
<li>repeat the step 2 and 3 with LHS and RHS swapped, and update the lower bound with the larger one.</li>
</ul>

Definition at line <a href="#l01547">1547</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/ir/constantrange-cpp">ConstantRange.cpp</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

<Link id="l00008" /><CodeLine lineNumber="8"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00009" /><CodeLine lineNumber="9"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Represent a range of possible values that may occur when the program is run</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00010" /><CodeLine lineNumber="10"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// for an integral value.  This keeps track of a lower and upper bound for the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00011" /><CodeLine lineNumber="11"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// constant, which MAY wrap around the end of the numeric range.  To do this, it</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00012" /><CodeLine lineNumber="12"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// keeps track of a &#91;lower, upper) bound, which specifies an interval just like</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00013" /><CodeLine lineNumber="13"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// STL iterators.  When used with boolean values, the following are important</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00014" /><CodeLine lineNumber="14"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// ranges (other integral ranges use min/max values for special range values):</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00015" /><CodeLine lineNumber="15"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00016" /><CodeLine lineNumber="16"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  &#91;F, F) = &#123;&#125;     = Empty set</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00017" /><CodeLine lineNumber="17"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  &#91;T, F) = &#123;T&#125;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00018" /><CodeLine lineNumber="18"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  &#91;F, T) = &#123;F&#125;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00019" /><CodeLine lineNumber="19"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//  &#91;T, T) = &#123;F, T&#125; = Full set</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00020" /><CodeLine lineNumber="20"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01522" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1522"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01523" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1523"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Estimate the &#39;bit-masked AND&#39; operation&#39;s lower bound.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01524" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1524"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01525" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1525"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// E.g., given two ranges as follows (single quotes are separators and</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01526" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1526"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// have no meaning here),</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01527" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1527"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01528" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1528"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///   LHS = &#91;10&#39;00101&#39;1,  ; LLo</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01529" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1529"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///          10&#39;10000&#39;0&#93;  ; LHi</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01530" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1530"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///   RHS = &#91;10&#39;11111&#39;0,  ; RLo</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01531" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1531"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///          10&#39;11111&#39;1&#93;  ; RHi</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01532" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1532"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01533" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1533"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// we know that the higher 2 bits of the result is always 10; and we also</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01534" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1534"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// notice that RHS&#91;1:6&#93; are always 1, so the result&#91;1:6&#93; cannot be less than</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01535" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1535"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// LHS&#91;1:6&#93; (i.e., 00101). Thus, the lower bound is 10&#39;00101&#39;0.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01536" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1536"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01537" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1537"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// The algorithm is as follows,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01538" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1538"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// 1 we first calculate a mask to find the higher common bits by</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01539" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1539"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///       Mask = ~((LLo ^ LHi) | (RLo ^ RHi) | (LLo ^ RLo));</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01540" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1540"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///       Mask = clear all non-leading-ones bits in Mask;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01541" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1541"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///    in the example, the Mask is set to 11&#39;00000&#39;0;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01542" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1542"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// 2 calculate a new mask by setting all common leading bits to 1 in RHS, and</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01543" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1543"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///    keeping the longest leading ones (i.e., 11&#39;11111&#39;0 in the example);</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01544" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1544"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// 3 return (LLo &amp; new mask) as the lower bound;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01545" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1545"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// 4 repeat the step 2 and 3 with LHS and RHS swapped, and update the lower</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01546" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1546"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///    bound with the larger one.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01547" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1547" lineLink="#a437967d8acddbcdb8cb345412f22f9dd"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">static</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/apint">APInt</a> <a href="#a437967d8acddbcdb8cb345412f22f9dd">estimateBitMaskedAndLowerBound</a>(</span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">const</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/constantrange">ConstantRange</a> &amp;<a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/target/lib/target/x86/x86partialreduction-cpp/#a9e1483f7215664a2315c53c3558d9a8d">LHS</a>,</span></CodeLine>
